nergism', 'The risk of hepatic injury should be considered when brentuximab vedotin is used with other agents that are potentially hepatotoxic (e.', 'Moderate', 'pharmacodynamic', NULL, 'https://ddinter2.scbdd.com/server/interact/15134/', '', 'Brivaracetam, Topiramate, Cenobamate, Lamotrigine, Methylphenobarbital, Ethosuximide, Lacosamide, Levetiracetam, Tiagabine, Oxcarbazepine, Rufinamide, More', 'Pertuzumab, Cetuximab, Avelumab, Panitumumab, Obinutuzumab, Bevacizumab, Necitumumab, Dostarlimab, Ramucirumab, Atezolizumab, Amivantamab, More', 1767369485);
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO drug_interactions (id, ingredient1, ingredient2, severity, effect, source, management_text, mechanism_text, recommendation, risk_level, type, metabolism_info, source_url, reference_text, alternatives_a, alternatives_b, updated_at) VALUES (15120, 'Fosphenytoin', 'Brexanolone', 'Moderate', 'Coadministration with central nervous system (CNS) depressants (e.g., alcohol, benzodiazepines, opioids) or antidepressants may enhance the sedative effects of brexanolone and increase the likelihood or severity of sedation-related adverse reactions. Patients treated with brexanolone are at risk of excessive sedation or sudden loss of consciousness during administration.', 'DDInter', 'Caution is advised during concomitant use of brexanolone with CNS depressants, antidepressants, or other agents that cause sedation. Patients should be closely monitored for excessive sedation and sudden loss of consciousness and have continuous pulse oximetry monitoring. During the brexanolone infusion, monitor for sedative effects every 2 hours during planned, non-sleep periods, and immediately stop the infusion if there are signs or symptoms of excessive sedation. After symptoms resolve, the infusion may be resumed at the same or lower dose as clinically appropriate. If pulse oximetry reveals hypoxia, immediately stop the infusion and do not resume infusion following resolution of the hypoxia. Patients should be cautioned against driving, operating machinery, or engaging in potentially hazardous activities requiring mental alertness and motor coordination until sedative effects of brexanolone and other concomitant medications have dissipated.', 'Synergism', 'Caution is advised during concomitant use of brexanolone with CNS depressants, antidepressants, or other agents that cause sedation.', 'Moderate', 'pharmacodynamic', NULL, 'https://ddinter2.scbdd.com/server/interact/15135/', '', 'Fenfluramine', '', 1767369485);
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO drug_interactions (id, ingredient1, ingredient2, severity, effect, source, management_text, mechanism_text, recommendation, risk_level, type, metabolism_info, source_url, reference_text, alternatives_a, alternatives_b, updated_at) VALUES (15121, 'Fosphenytoin', 'Brexpiprazole', 'Moderate', 'Coadministration with potent inducers of CYP450 3A4 may significantly decrease the plasma concentrations of brexpiprazole, which is partially metabolized by this isoenzyme. According to product labeling, administration of brexpiprazole with a potent 3A4 inducer (rifampin) resulted in an approximately 75% decrease in AUC.', 'DDInter', 'During concomitant use with a potent 3A4 inducer, the usual dose of brexpiprazole should be doubled over one to two weeks. When the inducer is discontinued, the brexpiprazole dose should be decreased to its original level over one to two weeks. It is advisable to monitor patients for clinical response.', 'Metabolism', 'During concomitant use with a potent 3A4 inducer, the usual dose of brexpiprazole should be doubled over one to two weeks.', 'Moderate', 'pharmacodynamic', NULL, 'https://ddinter2.scbdd.com/server/interact/15136/', '', 'Lacosamide', 'Amisulpride', 1767369485);
